	  <title>Exercises: Change of Coordinates</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>You are given the ordered basis <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}= (\Vect{b}_1,\Vect{b}_2)</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math>, where</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>\Vect{b}_1 = (1,3) \quad\text{and}\quad \Vect{b}_2 = (-2,-1)</latex>
			         </math.display>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the coordinate conversion matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}}</latex>
                     </math> from standard <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{S}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}} = \dfrac{1}{5}
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
-1 &amp; 2 \\
-3 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We know that the matrix which converts from <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates to standard coordinates has the vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{b}_1</latex>
                        </math> as its 1st column and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{b}_2</latex>
                        </math> as its second column. Therefore,</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}} = [ \Vect{b}_1\ \ \Vect{b}_2]</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We also know that the inverse of <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                        </math> converts from <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{S}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates to <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates. In symbols:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}} = \left(\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}\right)^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
1 &amp; -2 \\
3 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]^{-1}
=\dfrac{1}{5}\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
-1 &amp; 2 \\
-3 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Find <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math> if <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{S}} = (5,-4)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} = -\tfrac{1}{5}(13 , 19)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>You are given two ordered bases of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>:  <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\Vect{b}_2,\Vect{b}_3)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{C}=(\Vect{c}_1,\Vect{c}_2,\Vect{c}_3)</latex>
                  </math> with </para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>
					
\begin{array}{cclcclccl}
\Vect{b}_1 &amp; = &amp; (1,0,1) &amp; \Vect{b}_2 &amp; = &amp; (-1,-1,0) &amp; \Vect{b}_3 &amp; = &amp; (0,-1,-1) \\
\Vect{c}_1 &amp; = &amp; (1,0,0) &amp; \Vect{c}_2 &amp; = &amp; (-1,-1,1) &amp; \Vect{c}_3 &amp; = &amp; (0,0,2)
\end{array}

				</latex>
			         </math.display>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the coordinate conversion matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math> from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} = 
\dfrac{1}{2}\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
0 &amp; 2 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -2
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We construct the required coordinate conversion matrix conveniently as</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{S}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is indeed convenient because we know</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>and</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{S}} = \left( \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{C}}\right)^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]^{-1}

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>With the row reduction method, we obtain</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]^{-1} = 
\dfrac{1}{2} \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore we obtain</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} = \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{S}} \cdot \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}} = 
\dfrac{1}{2}\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
0 &amp; 2 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -2
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} = (2,0,-1)</latex>
                     </math>, find <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}} = (1,-1,2)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall:</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}\cdot \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>You are given two ordered bases <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_n)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{C}=(\Vect{c}_1,\dots ,\Vect{c}_n)</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Show that the RREF of the <math>
                        <latex>(n,2n)</latex>
                     </math>-matrix <math>
                        <latex>[\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{C}}\ |\ \Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}]</latex>
                     </math> is the <math>
                        <latex>(n,2n)</latex>
                     </math>-matrix <math>
                        <latex>[\IdMtrx[n]\ |\ \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}</latex>
                     </math>, the coordinate conversion matrix from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates, given the bases</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\Vect{b}_2,\Vect{b}_3,\Vect{b}_4) \quad\text{and}\quad \EuScript{C}=(\Vect{c}_1,\Vect{c}_2,\Vect{c}_3,\Vect{c}_4)</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                     </math>, where</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
\begin{array}{cclcclcclccl}
\Vect{b}_1 &amp; = &amp; (1,1,1,1) &amp; \Vect{b}_2 &amp; = &amp; (0,-1,0,1) \\ \Vect{b}_3 &amp; = &amp; (-1,0,-1,0) &amp; \Vect{b}_4 &amp; = &amp; (0,0,1,-1) \\
\Vect{c}_1 &amp; = &amp; (1,-1,1,2) &amp; \Vect{c}_2 &amp; = &amp; (4,1,3,1) \\ \Vect{c}_3 &amp; = &amp; (-1,2,-1,1) &amp; \Vect{c}_4 &amp; = &amp; (1,2,3,4)
\end{array}

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}} = 
\dfrac{1}{2}\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 8 \\
3 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \\
-1 &amp; -7 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\
0 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 &amp; 4
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>You are given two ordered bases <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_n)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{C}=(\Vect{c}_1,\dots ,\Vect{c}_n)</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>. For each of the following statements decide if it is true or false</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix which converts from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates is denoted <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix which converts from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates has size <math>
                        <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This coordinate conversion matrix has size <math>
                              <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                           </math>. So the statement in question is true only if <math>
                              <latex>n=3</latex>
                           </math>; in general it is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Review how this coordinate conversion matrix is constructed.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Is it possible that, no matter what number  <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math> represents, this coordinate conversion matrix always has the same size?</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix which converts from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates is invertible.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is true! - We proved that the inverse of <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                        </math> is the matrix which converts from <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates to <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix which converts from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates has rank <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall: a coordinate conversion matrix is always invertible.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We need to recall two facts</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ol>
						               <li>
							                 <para>
                           <para.body>This coordinate conversion matrix has size <math>
                                 <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
						               </li>
						               <li>
							                 <para>
                           <para.body>The matrix is invertible</para.body>
                        </para>
						               </li>
					             </ol>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Now we know that an invertible matrix of size <math>
                           <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                        </math> has the identity matrix of size <math>
                           <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                        </math> as its RREF, hence has rank <math>
                           <latex>n</latex>
                        </math>. So the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The determinant of the matrix which converts from <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates to <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates is nonzero.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Review previous parts of this problem.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We know that this coordinate conversion matrix is invertible. Therefore its determinant is nonzero.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
</exercise.pack>
